Virtual Machines (VMs) are extensively used in testing and development environments because they provide isolated, customizable, and scalable environments.

Developers can create multiple VMs with different operating systems, configurations, and software versions to test applications under various conditions.

For example, a developer building a web application can test it on both Windows and Linux VMs to ensure cross-platform compatibility.

A real-life use case is a software company running automated test pipelines. Each test case can spin up a fresh VM, run tests, and then destroy the VM to maintain a clean environment.

Another example is bug reproduction. Developers can replicate production issues in a controlled VM environment without affecting live systems.

VMs enable flexibility, isolation, and repeatability in development workflows.
